knitr document van Steensel lab

LAD rewiring data: CRISPRa in RPE cells – script to visualize repositioning of genes relative to the nuclear lamina.

Bas van Steensel, Nov 2018 – Feb 2019.

Introduction

This script plots figure panels of Brueckner et al.

Description of Data

  • DamID data preprocessed by Laura Brueckner. Input DamID data are read counts per GATC fragment.
  • Genome annotation is Ensembl build 75. This build is a bit old, but it is what the NKI Genomics Core Facility uses for RNAseq data processing. For consistency we use this build here as well.

Gene annotation data

Load Refseq annotations and convert to bed format dataframe. The latter is needed for the plotting of gene tracks using the Sushi package.

#Ensembl hg19 build 75 downloaded from    feb2014.archive.ensembl.org/biomart/martview/4c34fe2f4e47c6b55a212cc95e3c952b
#load:
Ensembl.75<-read.delim("./data/ensEMBL/hg19/ensEMBL75_GRCh37.p13.txt", head=TRUE, sep="\t", as.is=TRUE)
#select and rename columns to make a .bed like dataframe:
Ensembl.75<-Ensembl.75[,c(3,4,5,7,6,6,1)]
names(Ensembl.75)<-c("chrom", "start", "stop", "gene", "score","strand","ensembl.gene.id")
#only on full chromosomes:
Ensembl.75<-Ensembl.75[Ensembl.75$chrom %in% c(1:22,"X","Y"),]
#reformat some stuff:
Ensembl.75$chrom<-paste0("chr",Ensembl.75$chrom)
Ensembl.75$strand<-ifelse(Ensembl.75$strand==-1, "-", "+")
#remove redundancies
Ensembl.75<-unique(Ensembl.75)
#remove questionable genes (mostly absent in UCSC):
Ensembl.75<-Ensembl.75[-grep("^RP11", Ensembl.75$gene, value=FALSE),]
Ensembl.75<-Ensembl.75[-grep("^AC[0-9]{6}[.][0-9]*", Ensembl.75$gene, value=FALSE),]
Ensembl.75<-Ensembl.75[Ensembl.75$stop - Ensembl.75$start > 200,] #remove very small genes, as the plotGenes() function of Sushi cannot cope with them
#how many genes in the end:
dim(Ensembl.75)

#To automatically collect control data (== cntl plus ALL datasets not targeting the same chromosome)
#determine targeted chromosome for each dataset, put results into data.frame Eset:
keygene<-sub("_.*","", names(list_data_RPE))
gchrom2<-c()
for(g in 1:length(keygene))
{wh<-which(Ensembl.75$gene==keygene[g])
 gchrom2[g]<-as.character(unique(Ensembl.75$chrom[wh]))
}
gchrom2<-as.character(gchrom2)
gchrom2[1]<-"none"
Eset<-data.frame(dataset=names(list_data_RPE), keygene=keygene, chrom=gchrom2, stringsAsFactors=FALSE)
ControlSet<-which(Eset$chrom != unique(gchrom))


#convert relevant file name set to required format:
Exp.Dfiles<-unlist(list_data_RPE[[GN]][grep("_D_", names(list_data_RPE[[GN]]))])
Exp.DLfiles<-unlist(list_data_RPE[[GN]][grep("_DL_", names(list_data_RPE[[GN]]))])
Control.Dfiles<-c(); Control.DLfiles<-c()
for(i in ControlSet)
  {Control.Dfiles<-c(Control.Dfiles, unlist(list_data_RPE[[i]][grep("_D_", names(list_data_RPE[[i]]))]))
   Control.DLfiles<-c(Control.DLfiles, unlist(list_data_RPE[[i]][grep("_DL_", names(list_data_RPE[[i]]))]))
}
data.summ<-paste0("control (n = ", length(Control.DLfiles),"/", length(Control.Dfiles), ")")
data.summ[2]<-paste0("experimental (n = ", length(Exp.DLfiles),"/", length(Exp.Dfiles), ")")
print(data.summ)

Inspect data

How noisy are the data? Do they correlate well overall? Looks OK?

#scatter plot of Control vs Exp data:
notna<-!(is.na(mcols(sDamID.Exp)$logratio) | is.na(mcols(sDamID.Control)$logratio))
s<-sample(which(notna), 50000)
par(mfrow=c(1,1))
plot(mcols(sDamID.Control)$logratio[s], mcols(sDamID.Exp)$logratio[s], pch=19, cex=0.5, col="#00000022")
#highlight Exp gene:
COL<-rainbow(length(mygenes)) #plotting colors
for(g in 1:length(mygenes))
{w<-which(seqnames(sDamID.Exp)==gchrom[g] & start(sDamID.Exp)>=gstart[g] & end(sDamID.Exp)<=gstop[g])
 points(mcols(sDamID.Control)$logratio[w], mcols(sDamID.Exp)$logratio[w], pch=19, cex=0.5, col=COL[g])
 legend("topleft", pch=19, legend=mygenes, col=COL)
}
#correlation coefficients:
#pearson:
print(cor(mcols(sDamID.Control)$logratio, mcols(sDamID.Exp)$logratio, use="p", method="p"))

## [1] 0.974134

#spearman:
print(cor(mcols(sDamID.Control)$logratio, mcols(sDamID.Exp)$logratio, use="p", method="s"))

## [1] 0.9779721

#is slope close to 1:
LM<-lm(mcols(sDamID.Exp)$logratio ~ mcols(sDamID.Control)$logratio)
print(LM)

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = mcols(sDamID.Exp)$logratio ~ mcols(sDamID.Control)$logratio)
## 
## Coefficients:
##                    (Intercept)  mcols(sDamID.Control)$logratio  
##                     -0.0003138                       1.0363514

abline(LM, lwd=3, col="green")
abline(a=0, b=1, col="black", lty="dashed", lwd=3)
legend("bottomright", legend=c("diagonal", "linear fit"), col=c("black", "green"), lwd=3, lty=c("solid", "dashed"))


#use loess smoothing to straighten out banana-shapes etc:
#the reasonable assumption here is that most of the genome will remain unaffected, or at least will not show effects in the same direction.
#ord<-order(mcols(sDamID.Control)$logratio[s])
LOESS50<-loess(mcols(sDamID.Exp)$logratio[s]-mcols(sDamID.Control)$logratio[s] ~ mcols(sDamID.Control)$logratio[s], span=0.5)
#apply correction to experimental data:
mcols(sDamID.Exp)$logratio <- mcols(sDamID.Exp)$logratio - predict(LOESS50, mcols(sDamID.Control)$logratio)
#plot again: 
plot(mcols(sDamID.Control)$logratio[s], mcols(sDamID.Exp)$logratio[s], pch=19, cex=0.5, col="#00000022")
for(g in 1:length(mygenes))
{w<-which(seqnames(sDamID.Exp)==gchrom[g] & start(sDamID.Exp)>=gstart[g] & end(sDamID.Exp)<=gstop[g])
 points(mcols(sDamID.Control)$logratio[w], mcols(sDamID.Exp)$logratio[w], pch=19, cex=0.5, col=COL[g])
 legend("topleft", pch=19, legend=mygenes, col=COL)
}
LMcor<-lm(mcols(sDamID.Exp)$logratio[s] ~ mcols(sDamID.Control)$logratio[s])
abline(LMcor, lwd=3, col="green")
abline(a=0, b=1, col="black", lty="dashed", lwd=3)
legend("bottomright", legend=c("diagonal", "linear fit"), col=c("black", "green"), lwd=3, lty=c("solid", "dashed"))

Scores.exp<-findOverlapPairs(GeneGR, sDamID.Exp)@second@elementMetadata@listData$logratio
